30/05/2003
TIRANA, Albania -- The government decided Thursday (29 May) to remove visa requirements for citizens of seven Central and East European countries: Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Hungary, Croatia, Poland, Romania, and Bosnia and Herzegovina. 
Citizens of Italy and Greece also do not need visas to enter the country. 
After the cabinet meeting, Prime Minister Fatos Nano said liberalising the visa regime would accelerate regional integration processes.
In other news Thursday, Foreign Minister Ilir Meta met with the ambassador of Serbia-Montenegro, Cafo Kapetanovic.Afterwards, Meta said that signing a Free Trade Agreement. 
would be a priority in bilateral relations between the two countries. 
(Shekulli - 30/05/03; ATA - 29/05/03)
